items.abstract:
<jats:p>The 2-amine derivatives of 5-arylidene-3<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-4(5<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>)-one are a new class of bacterial efflux pump inhibitors, the chemical compounds that are able to restore antibiotic efficacy against multidrug resistant bacteria. 5-Arylidene-3<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-4(5<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>)-ones with a piperazine ring at position 2 reverse the mechanisms of multidrug resistance (MDR) of the particularly dangerous Gram-negative bacteria <jats:italic>E. coli</jats:italic> by inhibition of the efflux pump AcrA/AcrB/TolC (a main multidrug resistance mechanism in Gram-negative bacteria, consisting of a membrane fusion protein, AcrA, a Resistant-Nodulation-Division protein, AcrB, and an outer membrane factor, TolC). In order to study the influence of the environment on the conformation of (<jats:italic>Z</jats:italic>)-5-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-2-[4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl]-3<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-4(5<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>)-one, (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>), two different salts were prepared, namely with picolinic acid {systematic name: 4-[(<jats:italic>Z</jats:italic>)-4-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-5-oxo-3,4-dihydro-1<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-2-yl]-1-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-ium pyridine-2-carboxylate, C<jats:sub>16</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>20</jats:sub>ClN<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>
                  <jats:sup>+</jats:sup>·C<jats:sub>6</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>NO<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>
                  <jats:sup>−</jats:sup>, (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>
                  <jats:italic>
                     <jats:bold>a</jats:bold>
                  </jats:italic>)} and 4-nitrophenylacetic acid {systematic name: 4-[(<jats:italic>Z</jats:italic>)-4-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-5-oxo-3,4-dihydro-1<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-2-yl]-1-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-ium 2-(4-nitrophenyl)acetate, C<jats:sub>16</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>20</jats:sub>ClN<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>
                  <jats:sup>+</jats:sup>·C<jats:sub>8</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>6</jats:sub>NO<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>
                  <jats:sup>−</jats:sup>, (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>
                  <jats:italic>
                     <jats:bold>b</jats:bold>
                  </jats:italic>)}. The crystal structures of the new salts were determined by X-ray diffraction. In both crystal structures, the molecule of (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>) is protonated at an N atom of the piperazine ring by proton transfer from the corresponding acid. The carboxylate group of picolinate engages in hydrogen bonds with three molecules of the cation of (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>), whereas the carboxylate group of 4-nitrophenylacetate engages in hydrogen bonds with only two molecules of (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>). As a consequence of these interactions, different orientations of the hydroxyethyl group of (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>) are observed. The crystal structures are additionally stabilized by both C—H...N [in (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>
                  <jats:italic>
                     <jats:bold>a</jats:bold>
                  </jats:italic>)] and C—H...O [in (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>
                  <jats:italic>
                     <jats:bold>a</jats:bold>
                  </jats:italic>) and (<jats:bold>3</jats:bold>
                  <jats:italic>
                     <jats:bold>b</jats:bold>
                  </jats:italic>)] intermolecular interactions. The geometry of the imidazolone fragment was compared with other crystal structures possessing this moiety. The tautomer observed in the crystal structures presented here, namely 3<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-4(5<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>)-one [systematic name: 1<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-5(4<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>)-one], is also that most frequently observed in other structures containing this heterocycle.</jats:p>
title: Conformational study of (Z)-5-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-2-[4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl]-3H-imidazol-4(5H)-one in different environments: insight into the structural properties of bacterial efflux pump inhibitors

items.abstract:
<jats:p>The arylidene–imidazolone derivatives are a group of compounds of great interest in medicinal chemistry due to their various pharmacological actions. In order to study the possible conformations of an arylidene–imidazolone derivative, two new crystal structures were determined by X-ray diffraction, namely (<jats:italic>Z</jats:italic>)-5-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-2-(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)-3<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-5(4<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>)-one, C<jats:sub>15</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>17</jats:sub>ClN<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>O, (<jats:bold>6</jats:bold>), and its salt 4-[5-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-5-oxo-4,5-dihydro-3<jats:italic>H</jats:italic>-imidazol-2-yl]-1-methylpiperazin-1-ium 3-{5-[4-(diethylamino)benzylidene]-4-oxo-2-thioxothiazolidin-3-yl}propionate, C<jats:sub>15</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>18</jats:sub>ClN<jats:sub>4</jats:sub>O<jats:sup>+</jats:sup>·C<jats:sub>17</jats:sub>H<jats:sub>19</jats:sub>N<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>O<jats:sub>3</jats:sub>S<jats:sub>2</jats:sub>
                  <jats:sup>−</jats:sup>, (<jats:bold>7</jats:bold>). Both compounds crystallize in the space group <jats:italic>P</jats:italic>-1. The basic form (<jats:bold>6</jats:bold>) crystallizes with two molecules in the asymmetric unit. In the acid form of (<jats:bold>6</jats:bold>), the N atom of the piperazine ring is protonated by proton transfer from the carboxyl group of the rhodanine acid derivative. The greatest difference in the conformations of (<jats:bold>6</jats:bold>) and its protonated form, (<jats:bold>6c</jats:bold>), is observed in the location of the arylidene–imidazolone substituent at the N atom. In the case of (<jats:bold>6c</jats:bold>), the position of this substituent is close to axial, while for (<jats:bold>6</jats:bold>), the corresponding position is intermediate between equatorial and axial. The crystal packing is dominated by a network of N—H...O hydrogen bonds. Furthermore, the crystal structures are stabilized by numerous intermolecular contacts of types C—H...N and C—H...Cl in (<jats:bold>6</jats:bold>), and C—H...O and C—H...S in (<jats:bold>7</jats:bold>). The geometry with respect to the location of the substituents at the N atoms of the piperazine ring was compared with other crystal structures possessing an <jats:italic>N</jats:italic>-methylpiperazine moiety.</jats:p>
title: Influence of 3-{5-[4-(diethylamino)benzylidene]rhodanine}propionic acid on the conformation of 5-(4-chlorobenzylidene)-2-(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)-3H-imidazol-4(5H)-one
